    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3083649598" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3083649598" />
    <a title="Jim" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/695116-jim"><img alt="Jim" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1340192527p2/695116.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3083649598?book_show_action=true">Dec 13, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jim" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jim" href="/user/show/695116-jim">Jim</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audio CD 9781455883400" href="/book/show/15022646-alas-babylon">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/695116-jim?shelf=2fiction">2fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/695116-jim?shelf=apocalyptic">apocalyptic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/695116-jim?shelf=scifi">scifi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/695116-jim?shelf=1audio">1audio</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/695116-jim?shelf=historical">historical</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3083649598" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9160445726833011934">This book is 60 years old, but well worth reading &amp; not just for its influence on the genre. It&apos;s one of the first to deal with a post apocalyptic world after a nuclear war, so it&apos;s not pretty, but it is instructive on many levels &amp; an entertaining read. It should be a Thanksgiving Day read in the US because it shows how much we have to be grateful for: electricity, clean water delivered to the tap, good food, medicines, medical care, &amp; relative order.<br/><br/>Frank really sets the scene well. Fort Repos</span>
  <span id="freeText9160445726833011934" style="display:none">This book is 60 years old, but well worth reading &amp; not just for its influence on the genre. It's one of the first to deal with a post apocalyptic world after a nuclear war, so it's not pretty, but it is instructive on many levels &amp; an entertaining read. It should be a Thanksgiving Day read in the US because it shows how much we have to be grateful for: electricity, clean water delivered to the tap, good food, medicines, medical care, &amp; relative order.<br /><br />Frank really sets the scene well. Fort Repose reminds me a lot of the small town where I lived on the Eastern Shore of Maryland. It's very southern &amp; I lived there in the mid 60s, so not long after this book was published. The racial issues were about the same, almost a complete separation between races, although the public school was desegregated when I went there. Not everyone was happy about that on either side. There's a telling sentence when Randy, one of the least prejudiced characters, realizes the new school will be desegregated.<br /><br />I really liked the way Mark explains the situation to Randy. Not only does it fill me in on the state of the world, but it does so in a logical way that eases the data dump. The seeds of MAD are clearly shown as are the reasons behind JFK's space race. Later, the retired admiral expands a bit on this pointing out how all the upper level thinking was tactical, none strategic. They're important points to remember for the last bit of the novel. Wow! Frank really knocks the point home.<br /><br />As I read through this, I had a feeling Frank could have gone into a lot more detail, but I'm glad he didn't. He addressed the main points &amp; let characterization fill in much of the rest. Some people rose to the occasion, some couldn't live with it, others just slowly decayed. Florence was a hoot &amp; a great hook to explain so much of the everyday life. While there was greed &amp; some violence, the book never resorted to gore or outrageous action. It was always real people dealing with a very scary &amp; realistic situation. It highlights how unprepared &amp; useless the 'best' of society could be &amp; how well prepared some of the 'least' were, especially the so-called second class citizens of the day. The need for some specialists, such as a doctor were also well displayed.<br /><br />I've read quite a few post apocalyptic novels over the years. Many are nothing more than action-porn, entertaining, but not not particularly filling. If you like this, I highly recommend <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/4922079.One_Second_After__After___1_" title="One Second After (After, #1) by William R. Forstchen" rel="nofollow noopener">One Second After</a> an update of this book &amp; <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1689657.World_Made_by_Hand__World_Made_by_Hand__1_" title="World Made by Hand (World Made by Hand #1) by James Howard Kunstler" rel="nofollow noopener">World Made by Hand</a> which shows it doesn't take a cataclysmic event to bring down civilization. <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38180.On_the_Beach" title="On the Beach by Nevil Shute" rel="nofollow noopener">On the Beach</a> was written a few year later than <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38169.Alas__Babylon" title="Alas, Babylon by Pat Frank" rel="nofollow noopener">Alas, Babylon</a> about a much worse nuclear war. About a decade before, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/93269.Earth_Abides" title="Earth Abides by George R. Stewart" rel="nofollow noopener">Earth Abides</a> shows a world where almost all the humans die due to a disease, an update of Shelley's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/966835.The_Last_Man" title="The Last Man by Mary Wollstonecraft Shelley" rel="nofollow noopener">The Last Man</a> &amp; far more readable.<br /><br />This was my first time reading it as an audiobook &amp; it was wonderful. I read this this time with the Evolution of SF group here:<br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/topic/show/20881124">https://www.goodreads.com/topic/show/...</a><br />I last read this in 2013 as a PB. My 5 star review is here:<br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/51392664">https://www.goodreads.com/review/show...</a><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9160445726833011934" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


