    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_609572409" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/609572409" />
    <a title="Kelly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/773729-kelly"><img alt="Kelly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1541106076p2/773729.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/609572409?book_show_action=true">May 07, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kelly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kelly" href="/user/show/773729-kelly">Kelly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/773729-kelly?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/773729-kelly?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/773729-kelly?shelf=sf">sf</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer609572409" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8158701421210366433">&quot;The classic apocalyptic novel that stunned the world&quot; is across the front cover of this book. It was written in 1959 when fear of the atomic bomb was all-encompassing so I can only imagine how stunned people were to read this book when it came out. <br/><br/>The last apocalyptic novel I read was <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6288.The_Road' title='The Road by Cormac McCarthy' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Road</a> and it was incredibly depressing. This one wasn&apos;t...while at times this book was chilling, it was filled with goodness and hope. In fact, it was a mirror image of the way I&apos;ve always pictured things woul</span>
  <span id="freeText8158701421210366433" style="display:none">"The classic apocalyptic novel that stunned the world" is across the front cover of this book. It was written in 1959 when fear of the atomic bomb was all-encompassing so I can only imagine how stunned people were to read this book when it came out. <br /><br />The last apocalyptic novel I read was <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6288.The_Road" title="The Road by Cormac McCarthy" rel="nofollow noopener">The Road</a> and it was incredibly depressing. This one wasn't...while at times this book was chilling, it was filled with goodness and hope. In fact, it was a mirror image of the way I've always pictured things would go down in case of a nuclear war. Well, maybe not exactly a mirror image; the author included many things I hadn't really thought about and, believe me, I did a lot of thinking while reading this book. I don't really think it will ever come down to this kind of global catastrophe, but I've definitely done a lot of thinking while reading this book...and I'm still thinking. Due to this fact I gave it 5 stars instead of 4.<br /><br />**POTENTIAL SPOILERS BELOW**<br /><br />The lawlessness scared me the most. That being said, I truly believe the majority of people would be like those in this book...neighbors/family/friends/communities helping one another. There were some who were too weak (physically/mentally/emotionally) to survive the shock long enough to stabilize into a "new normal". I truly think my neighborhood would pull together like the main characters in this book...into a little tribe, everyone finding their niche and providing for some need of the community. They had to protect each other from those who would steal from or hurt them. I thought it was interesting that after a manner of months they settled into a routine and everything went back to how it used to be without goods being shipped via plane/train/truck...they ate things in season, whatever was growing/living where they lived at the immediate time. They had to figure out where to get salt, how to use things they had to create other things they needed. It was very interesting to read.<br /><br />I think this quote from the commentary at the end of the book by Hal Hager sums this book up very well:<br /><br />"...Alas, Babylon was to be among the first to give a public voice to the fears and anxieties associated with a nuclear attack and with threats of atomic radiation. And unlike others in the genre, he offered unmitigated hope. Randy Bragg and company not only survive the devastation that leaves vast Contaminated Zones throughout the United States, but they also apply the best in themselves to begin the re-establishment of life within a civil society. All of the atomic fears of the 1950s (and later) are there, but Frank's 'message' seems to be that we can survive even the worst catastrophe with everyday, secularized applications of faith, hope, and charity."</span>
  <a data-text-id="8158701421210366433" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


